"attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname for a person with a cheerful disposition, from Middle English <i>seli</i> ‘happy, fortunate’ (Old English <i>sǣlig</i>, from <i>sǣl</i> ‘happiness, good fortune’). The word was also occasionally used as a female personal name during the Middle Ages. The sense ‘pitiable’, which developed into modern English <i>silly</i>, is not attested before the 15th century. See also   Selman  .","Altered form of German   Seele  , respelled to preserve the bisyllabic pronunciation of the German name."],"variants":[{"name":"Seely","meanings":["English (East Anglia): variant of   Seeley  ."]},{"name":"Selley","meanings":["English (Devon):","variant of   Seeley  .","habitational name from Selly Oak in Northfield (Worcestershire), probably from Old English <i>scelf</i> ‘shelf, ledge’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’."]},{"name":"Selman","meanings":["English: nickname for a happy or fortunate man, from Middle English <i>seli</i> ‘happy, fortunate’ (Old English <i>sǣlig</i>) + <i>man</i>. The nickname was also used as a personal name. See also   Seeley  .","English: from the Middle English nickname or female personal name <i>Sely</i> (see   Seeley  ) + <i>-man</i>, hence an occupational name for a servant of someone so called.","Americanized form of German <b>Sellmann</b> (see   Sellman  )."]},{"name":"Seelye","meanings":["English: variant of   Seeley  ."]},{"name":"Sealy","meanings":["English: variant of   Seeley  .","Welsh: from the male personal name <i>Selyf</i> or <i>Seleu</i>, medieval Welsh vernacular forms of   Solomon   which were replaced by that form in the Welsh Bible of 1588.","Irish: variant of   Shelley   (in counties Cork and Kerry); elsewhere of English or Welsh origin, as in 1 above and 2."]},{"name":"Sealey","meanings":["English: variant of   Seeley  ."]},{"name":"Seley","meanings":["English: variant of   Seeley  . This form of the surname is now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Nathaniel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of a New Testament name, which is derived from the Greek form of a Hebrew name meaning ‘God has given’ (  compare  Nathan  , which is sometimes taken as a short form of this name). It was borne by one of the less prominent of Christ's apostles (John 1:45; 21:2), who in fact is probably identical with   Bartholomew .  The spelling used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament is  <b>Nathanael</b> , but this is in much less frequent use as a given name in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Nathaniel Seeley was born in 1420, in Great Gransden, Huntingdonshire, England, his father, John Seeley, was 27 and his mother, Martha Benjamin, was 25. He had at least 2 sons with Rebecca Hubbell. He died in 1447, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 27."},"et":{"1420–1447":"1420–1447","1418–Male":"1418–Surnud","1447–1465":"1447–1465","1447–Male":"1447–Surnud","1393–1442":"1393–1442","1395–1420":"1395–1420","1447 ":"1447","1447":"1447","1465":"1465","1420":"1420","1442":"1442","1395":"1395","1393":"1393","1418":"1418","Great Gransden, Huntingdonshire, England":"Great Gransden, Huntingdonshire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hereford, Herefordshire, England":"Hereford, Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1420–1447":"1420–1447","1418–Male":"1418–Kuollut","1447–1465":"1447–1465","1447–Male":"1447–Kuollut","1393–1442":"1393–1442","1395–1420":"1395–1420","1447 ":"1447","1447":"1447","1465":"1465","1420":"1420","1442":"1442","1395":"1395","1393":"1393","1418":"1418","Great Gransden, Huntingdonshire, England":"Great Gransden, Huntingdonshire, England","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Hereford, Herefordshire, England":"Hereford, Herefordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1420–1447":"1420–1447","1418–Male":"1418–Décédé","1447–1465":"